3":"1222–1283","1224–1249":"1224–1249","1242–Male":"1242–Afdød","1244–Female":"1244–Afdød","1245–1312":"1245–1312","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","about 1239":"omkring 1239","1312":"1312","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1242":"1242","about 1244":"omkring 1244","1283":"1283","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Bunbury, Cheshire, England","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"1222–1283":"1222–1283","1224–1249":"1224–1249","1242–Male":"1242–Overleden","1244–Female":"1244–Overleden","1245–1312":"1245–1312","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","about 1239":"circa 1239","1312":"1312","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1242":"1242","about 1244":"circa 1244","1283":"1283","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Bunbury, Cheshire, England","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1222–1283":"1222–1283","1224–1249":"1224–1249","1242–Male":"1242–Deceased","1244–Female":"1244–Deceased","1245–1312":"1245–1312","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","about 1239":"about 1239","1312":"1312","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1242":"1242","about 1244":"about 1244","1283":"1283","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Bunbury, Cheshire, England","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beeston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of the many places in England so called. Those in Nottinghamshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire were settlements where bent grass grew (Old English <i>bēos</i> ‘rough grass’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’). In Bedfordshire it probably denoted a settlement on a bend (Old English <i>byge</i> + genitive singular <i>-es</i> + <i>tūn</i>). The hamlet stands on a marked bend of the river Yvel. In Cheshire it is named from a rock, below which trading took place (Old English <i>byge</i> ‘commerce’ + Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’). The reference is to a prominent crag where the remains of Beeston Castle stand. Compare   Beaston   and   Beeson  .","occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived in that part of a village known in Middle English as <i>bi este toun</i> ‘(place) at the east (end) of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   and   Beaston  ."]},{"name":"Beeson","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston  , a habitational name from a place called Beeston. The spelling reflects the local pronunciation of the Nottinghamshire placename, although this form is now quite widespread in England."]},{"name":"Beaston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   (the more common form of the surname in England), a habitational name from any of various places called Beeston."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":2,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":37,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Henry de Beeston was born in 1222, in Bunbury, Cheshire, England. He married Margery Beeston about 1239, in Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1283, in Beeston, Cheshire, England, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1222–1283":"1222–1283","1224–1249":"1224–1249","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","1245–1312":"1245–1312","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","about 1239":"umbes 1239","1312":"1312","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1242":"1242","about 1244":"umbes 1244","1283":"1283","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Bunbury, Cheshire, England","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1222–1283":"1222–1283","1224–1249":"1224–1249","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","1244–Female":"1244–Kuollut","1245–1312":"1245–1312","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","about 1239":"noin 1239","1312":"1312","1224":"1224","1245":"12